	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-1202328">

		
		<div class="comment-header">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
								<cite class="fn">E. Rhym</cite>				 <span class="says">(<a rel="nofollow" href="/history/?c=1202328">History</a>)</span>		 	</div>

			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				November 6, 2019 at 3:39 pm							</div>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Mr. Krepon, the United States will NOT withdraw from the New START treaty.  The Parties may permit New START to expire &#8212; just as they permitted the original START treaty to expire (without a replacement ready to supersede it I might add), but an agreement expiring under its own agreed terms does NOT constitute unilateral withdrawal.</p>
<p>New START, as START was before it, was limited in duration by design.  Both Parties did this for a reason, in order to assess the security environment &#8212; including technological change &#8212; a decade hence, so that a proper course correction could be pursued, either with or without a formal agreement.</p>
<p>Accordingly, there is nothing untoward about allowing New START to run its course under its own terms, just like the original START treaty.   And there is very good reason for the United States to pursue this course, given Russia&#8217;s actions &#8212; a topic I would be more than happy to engage anyone about in further detail.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="reply">
			<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/archive/1208302/norm-building-and-tear-downs/?replytocom=1202328#respond' data-commentid="1202328" data-postid="1208302" data-belowelement="comment-1202328" data-respondelement="respond" aria-label='Reply to E. Rhym'>Reply</a>		</div>

		</li><!-- #comment-## -->
